


	      THE LATEST VERSION OF THOR 



    INSTALLATION FROM THE ORIGINAL DISK

To install Thor, create a directory to contain the program on your hard
disk (for example, "MD \THOR"). Then move into this directory (with
"CD \THOR" for example, if the directory was created as above).

Next, insert the original disk into the floppy drive, and run the
installation program (if the floppy disk is drive A, type "A:INSTALL").

The installation program uncompresses files from the floppy disk onto
the hard disk. The name of each file is displayed as it is being copied,
along with the percentage of that file currently transferred. If an
error occurs while reading the floppy disk or writing to the hard disk,
installation terminates with an error message explaining the problem.

Repeat this procedure for each disk (if more than one).


    ERROR MESSAGES

    Error reading source disk
Indicates an error while reading the floppy diskette. This could be
due either to a faulty disk, to improper human intervention (such as 
removing the disk during installation), or to an inability to read the
disk (perhaps due to an alignment incompatibility).

    Error writing to destination disk
Indicates a write error caused when either there is a physical problem 
with the disk, when there's no diskette in the drive, when the destination
disk is write protected, or when the file currently being copied already
exists.

    Incorrect DOS version
or  source disk not recognized
Indicates either that a version of MS-DOS (or its equivalent, for example
DR-DOS) prior to version 3.0 is being used, or that the named source drive
does not exist. The installation program has been tested on all versions
of MS-DOS and this message should not appear. If you still use an earlier
version of MS-DOS, you'll have to upgrade your DOS version.


    DOWNLOADING

It's possible that you obtained this program electronically, rather 
that from an original disk. In this case, the installation procedure 
consists of downloading (and perhaps uncompressing) the required files
from the appropriate directory.

To do this, follow the standard procedure given by the site from which
you have downloaded the program.



